From f6afa5c304f2681ed30e9c3197a24e2fb5d2e2a4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jason Gross <jason@theorem.dev>
Date: Thu, 16 Jul 2026 02:16:09 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 3/3] arm: do not set the SBZ bits 15-12 when emitting CMP in
 gen_opi
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The comparison operators fall through gen_opi's generic
data-processing path, which allocates a scratch register r and ORs
r<<12 into the instruction — but for CMP (opc 0x15) bits 15-12 are
SBZ. `cmp r1, #0` was emitted as 0xe3511000 instead of 0xe3510000.

Real ARM cores ignore the SBZ field, so this goes unnoticed on
hardware; a strict decoder such as qemu treats the encoding as
UNPREDICTABLE and raises SIGILL (verified on qemu-arm 7.2, 8.2 and
10.0). It only manifests when the scratch register is not r0, e.g.
any `while (s[i])`-style loop whose condition reads memory — so
strlen, puts, printf all die under qemu. A gcc-built tcc from the
same source emits the same bad encoding, confirming a source bug.

The fix deliberately uses if/else rather than a `is_cmp?0:(r<<12)`
ternary inside the o(...) argument: MesCC (which this fork exists to
be compiled by) miscompiles a `cond?0:expr` ternary appearing as a
non-final term of an OR-chain in a call argument — the same
limitation the existing #if !BOOTSTRAP guards elsewhere in this file
work around.

With this fix tcc-compiled test programs run correctly under qemu,
and tcc self-hosts (verified with a gcc-built tcc of this source).

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_0135X6tRviSFCswBbHXxQofc
---
 arm-gen.c | 15 +++++++++++++--
 1 file changed, 13 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/arm-gen.c b/arm-gen.c
index eaddad31..1328ea3a 100644
--- a/arm-gen.c
+++ b/arm-gen.c
@@ -1638,19 +1638,30 @@ void gen_opi(int op)
       vswap();
       c=intr(gv(RC_INT));
       vswap();
+      /* opc==0x15 is CMP (the comparison ops fall through the `default` case
+	 above). CMP has no destination: bits 15-12 are SBZ. The generic path
+	 below allocates a scratch reg `r` and ORs it into that field; real ARM
+	 ignores those bits, but a strict decoder (qemu) faults on the resulting
+	 UNPREDICTABLE encoding. Only ORs r<<12 when there is a real result. */
+      { int is_cmp = (opc == 0x15);
       opc=0xE0000000|(opc<<20)|(c<<16);
       if((vtop->r & (VT_VALMASK | VT_LVAL | VT_SYM)) == VT_CONST) {
 	uint32_t x;
 	x=stuff_const(opc|0x2000000,vtop->c.i);
 	if(x) {
 	  r=intr(vtop[-1].r=get_reg_ex(RC_INT,regmask(vtop[-1].r)));
-	  o(x|(r<<12));
+	  /* NB: if/else, not `o(x|(is_cmp?0:(r<<12)))`: MesCC miscompiles a
+	     `cond?0:expr` ternary used as a non-final term of a |-chain passed
+	     as a call argument (it drops the other terms), so the ternary form
+	     emits a 0x00000000 word for every add. gcc handles it fine. */
+	  if (is_cmp) o(x); else o(x|(r<<12));
 	  goto done;
 	}
       }
       fr=intr(gv(RC_INT));
       r=intr(vtop[-1].r=get_reg_ex(RC_INT,two2mask(vtop->r,vtop[-1].r)));
-      o(opc|(r<<12)|fr);
+      if (is_cmp) o(opc|fr); else o(opc|(r<<12)|fr);
+      }
 done:
       vtop--;
       if (op >= TOK_ULT && op <= TOK_GT) {
-- 
